{"accepted":[{"assertion":"Erdős Problem #677: declared status 'open'. Formalized: yes. Let $M(n,k)=[n+1,\\ldots,n+k]$ be the least common multiple of $\\{n+1,\\ldots,n+k\\}$.\n\nIs it true that for all $m\\geq n+k$\\[M(n,k) \\neq M(m,k)?\\] Current best: The Thue-Siegel theorem implies that, for fixed $k$, there are only finitely many $m,n$ such that $m\\geq n+k$ and $M(n,k)=M(m,k)$. In general, how many solutions does $M(n,k)=M(m,l)$ have when $m\\geq n+k$ and $l>1$? Erd\\H{o}s expects very few (and none when $l\\geq k$). In \\cite{Er79d} Erd\\H{o}s conjectures the stronger fact that (aside from a finite number of exceptions) if $k>2$ and $m\\geq n+k$ then $\\prod_{i\\leq k}(n+i)$ and $\\prod_{i\\leq k}(m+i)$ cannot have the same set of prime factors. Prize: no. Tags: number theory.","id":"vf_54c0bbd21be136ed","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"},{"assertion":"Formal-Conjectures statement: Erdos677.erdos_677 https://google-deepmind.github.io/formal-conjectures/theorem/?name=Erdos677.erdos_677.","id":"vf_e8fa6dd66ed981df","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"}],"accepted_activity":false,"activity":[],"activity_types":[],"attempt_count":0,"banked_attempt_count":0,"commits":[],"dependency_impact":"none","detail_url":"problems/677.json","draft_proposals":[],"edges":[{"evidence":"Problem identity derived from the accepted finding's pinned source anchor.","inferred":true,"relation":"describes","source":"vf_54c0bbd21be136ed","source_root":"sha256:d3db36661e28b7570fc8704bf8455b80d8382beded47d069f2c386144d90a238","target":"erdos:677","trust":"signed"},{"evidence":"Problem identity derived from the accepted finding's pinned source anchor.","inferred":true,"relation":"describes","source":"vf_e8fa6dd66ed981df","source_root":"sha256:d3db36661e28b7570fc8704bf8455b80d8382beded47d069f2c386144d90a238","target":"erdos:677","trust":"signed"},{"evidence":"Materialized typed link between accepted findings.","inferred":true,"relation":"synthesized_from","source":"vf_e8fa6dd66ed981df"